To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino, you will need to follow the steps below:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to the Arduino board. The LM35 temperature sensor is powered by an Arduino board via VCC & GND pins. The analog output pin of the LM35 temperature sensor is connected to the analog input pin A0 of Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].
2. Connect the LCD to the Arduino board. The second pin of the potentiometer is connected to pin 3 of the LCD, and the first pin of the potentiometer is connected to +VCC. The LCD is controlled by the Arduino board using the LiquidCrystal library [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)].
3. Install the LiquidCrystal\_I2C library by Frank de Brabander in the Arduino IDE. This library is used to control the LCD display [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].
4. Write the code to read the temperature from the LM35 sensor and display it on the LCD. The code can be found in the Arduino tutorial on ArduinoGetStarted [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)].
5. Upload the code to the Arduino board.
6. Adjust the brightness of the LCD using the potentiometer.

By following these steps, you can create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino. The LCD will display the temperature read from the LM35 sensor, and the brightness of the LCD can be adjusted using the potentiometer.

A product designer is responsible for creating new products or improving existing ones. The process typically involves the following steps:

1. Research and Analysis: The designer conducts market research to understand the needs and preferences of the target audience. They also analyze the competition and identify any gaps in the market.
2. Concept Development: Based on the research, the designer develops several concepts for the new product. They sketch or create digital renderings of the concepts to visualize the product.
3. Prototyping: The designer creates a prototype of the most promising concept. This can be a physical model or a digital simulation. The prototype is used to test the product's functionality, usability, and aesthetics.
4. Testing and Evaluation: The prototype is tested with a small group of users to gather feedback. The designer evaluates the feedback and makes any necessary adjustments to the design.
5. Refinement: Based on the testing and evaluation, the designer refines the design and creates a final prototype. This prototype is used for manufacturing and production.
6. Manufacturing and Production: The final prototype is used to create the production-ready version of the product. The designer works with manufacturers to ensure that the product is produced to their specifications.
7. Launch and Marketing: The product is launched and marketed to the target audience. The designer may work with marketing teams to create promotional materials and campaigns.
